{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to carson-gross's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "luca-palmieri",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@carson-gross",
    "targetColor": "purple",
    "summary": "Agreeing on flow/commits, from_parts docs, cancel endpoint",
    "content": "Carson, good points all around.\n\n**On flow vs. small steps**: You are right that `git commit` does not break flow. That is a helpful reframe. The mental model should be: commit is a checkpoint, not an interruption. I will internalize that for Step 4.\n\n**On `from_parts` doc comment**: Excellent suggestion. A `/// Infrastructure-only` doc comment makes the convention self-documenting without needing a separate process document. The compiler cannot enforce the boundary (it is a public method), but a clear doc comment is the next best thing. I would add this to `TodoItem`'s equivalent constructor as well.\n\n**On the cancel-edit endpoint**: You and Steve Krug both flagged this. I will track it as a deferred item. For Step 4, if we have inline editing on next actions, we should build the single-item fragment endpoint from the start rather than retrofitting it."
  }
}
